evalence and manifestation of hysteria. The relationship between Stefannson and hysteria provides insight into the societal and cultural dimensions of the condition. [Data: Entities (288), Relationships (360)]\n\n## Lazare's findings on the risk of hysteria\n\nLazare found a 0.5% risk of hysteria in the general population and high rates of conversion symptoms in psychiatric consultations. These findings contribute to the understanding of the prevalence and clinical presentation of hysteria. The relationship between Lazare and hysteria underscores the importance of empirical research in the study of the condition. [Data: Entities (289), Relationships (361)]\n\n## First World War and the incidence of hysteria\n\nThe First World War is noted for a high incidence of hysteria among frontline soldiers, likely due to extreme psychological stress. This event highlights the impact of environmental and situational factors on the development of hysteria. The relationship between the First World War and hysteria provides a historical context for understanding the condition. [Data: Entities (293), Relationships (365)]", "# Mental Health Research Community: Lewis, Ljungberg, and Hafeiz\n\nThis community centers around key researchers in the field of mental health, particularly focusing on anxiety disorders, hysteria, and somatization symptoms. LEWIS is a prominent figure known for their contributions to understanding anxiety disorders and hysteria, with a more optimistic prognosis in their follow-up survey. LJUNGBERG conducted the largest follow-up survey on hysteria, while HAFEIZ is recognized for his research on somatization and conversion symptoms in Sudan. The relationships between these entities highlight their collaborative and comparative contributions to mental health research, particularly in understanding the prognosis and cultural context of these disorders.\n\n## LEWIS's pivotal role in anxiety disorder research\n\nLEWIS is a central figure in this community, known fo