ymptoms. The country's high occurrence of these symptoms in outpatient settings highlights the complex interplay between mental health and cultural context. This research provides valuable insights into the patterns and frequency of somatization and conversion symptoms in Sudan, emphasizing the need for culturally sensitive mental health care approaches [Data: Entities (294); Relationships (364)].\n\n## Comparative research on hysteria prognosis\n\nThe relationship between LEWIS and LJUNGBERG highlights the importance of comparative research in understanding the prognosis of hysteria. While both researchers conducted follow-up surveys on hysteria, LEWIS's results were more optimistic. This comparative analysis provides a broader perspective on the long-term outcomes of hysteria and underscores the value of diverse research approaches in mental health studies [Data: Relationships (397)].", "# CCMD-2-R and Mental Health Classification\n\nThe community centers around the CCMD-2-R, a diagnostic system for mental health disorders in China, and its associated classifications, such as depressive neurosis and hysteria. The CCMD-2-R integrates traditional Chinese psychiatric terminology with modern diagnostic criteria, aligning with the ICD-10. This system plays a pivotal role in bridging cultural specificity and global clinical standards in mental health diagnosis.\n\n## CCMD-2-R as a key diagnostic framework\n\nThe CCMD-2-R is a critical diagnostic system in China, officially released in 1994. It serves as a bridge between traditional Chinese psychiatric practices and modern international standards, particularly the ICD-10. The system's integration of culturally specific terms, such as 'hysteria,' with globally recognized clinical descriptions highlights its dual focus on cultural relevance and international alignment. This makes the CCMD-2-R a significant tool in the Chinese mental health landscape, influencing both diagnosis and treatment practices. [Data: Entities (287)