hile retaining culturally specific terminology. By doing so, the CCMD-2-R facilitates the adoption of international best practices in mental health diagnosis and treatment within China, enhancing its impact on the country's mental health landscape. [Data: Entities (287), Relationships (358)]", "# Freud and the Early Psychoanalytic Movement\n\nThis community centers around Sigmund Freud, the founder of psychoanalysis, and his early collaborators and followers who played pivotal roles in the development and dissemination of psychoanalytic theory. Key entities include Freud, Josef Breuer, Paul Federn, Max Eitingon, and others who contributed to the foundational theories and practices of psychoanalysis. The relationships within this community highlight collaborations, mentorship, and the institutionalization of psychoanalysis through societies, journals, and training institutes.\n\n## Freud as the central figure in psychoanalysis\n\nSigmund Freud is the cornerstone of this community, having founded psychoanalysis and introduced groundbreaking concepts such as the unconscious mind, psychosexual development, and the structure of the psyche (id, ego, and superego). His work has had a lasting impact on psychology and mental health treatment, influencing both theory and therapeutic practices. Freud's relationships with other key figures in the community, such as Josef Breuer and Max Eitingon, were instrumental in the development and dissemination of psychoanalytic ideas [Data: Entities (13), Relationships (355, 768, 777, 792, 793, +more)].\n\n## Collaboration with Josef Breuer on hysteria research\n\nFreud's collaboration with Josef Breuer was foundational to the development of psychoanalysis. Together, they conducted research on hysteria, which led to the publication of 'Studies on Hysteria' in 1895. This work introduced the concept of the 'talking cure,' a precursor to modern psychoanalytic therapy. Their collaboration marked the beginning of Freud's exploration of the unconscious mind and its role in psychological disorders [Data: Entities (654), Relationships (768, 773)].\n\n## Institutionalization of psychoanalysis by Max Eitingon\n\nMax Eitingon played a significant role in the institutionalization of psychoanalysis. He was instrumental in establishing psychoanalytic societies, journals, and training institutes, which helped standardize and professionalize the field. Eitingon's efforts ensured the widespread dissemination and acceptance of Freud's theories, contributing to the growth of psychoanalysis as a recognized discipline [Data: Entities (663), Relationships (777)].\n\n## Paul Federn's contributions to ego psychology\n\nPaul Federn, an early follower of Freud, made significant contributions to the development of ego psychology. His work expanded on Freud's theories, particularly in understanding the ego's adaptive functions. Federn's contributions helped bridge the gap between psychoanalytic theory and practical therapeutic applications, further solidifying the field's foundation [Data: Entities (660), Relationships (774)].\n\n## Dissemination of Freud's work in the United States by Abraham Brill\n\nAbraham Arden Brill played a pivotal role in introducing and popularizing Freud's theories in the United States. He translated many of Freud's seminal works into English, making them accessible to a broader American audience. Brill's efforts were crucial in the dissemination and understanding of psychoanalytic thought in the U.S., establishing him as a key figure in the field [Data: Entities (666), Relationships (780)].\n\n## Ernest Jones's role in spreading psychoanalysis in the English-speaking world\n\nErnest Jones was a prominent psychoanalyst and biographer of Freud, known for his efforts in spreading psychoanalysis in the English-speaking world. He played a significant role in establishing psychoanalytic societies and journals, contributing to the growth and institutionalization of the field. Jones's work was instrumental in shaping the development and dissemination of psychoanalytic theory and practice [Data: Entities (667), Relationships (781)].\n\n## The Wednesday Evening Meetings as a forum for psychoanalytic development\n\nThe Wednesday Evening Meetings, hosted by Freud, were informal gatherings where psychoanalysts discussed and developed psychoanalytic theory and practice. These meetings were crucial in the early development of psychoanalysis, providing a platform for collaboration and the exchange of ideas among Freud and his followers [Data: Entities (658), Relationships (772)].\n\n## Freud's introduction of conversion hysteria\n\nFreud introduced the concept of conversion hysteria, now known as conversion disorder, which he linked to repressed sexual trauma. This concept was a significant contribution to the understanding of psychological disorders and their somatic manifestations. Freud's work on conversion hysteria laid the groundwork for further research into the relationship between the mind and body in psychological illness [Data: Entities (295), Relationships (355)].", "# Adler, Jung, and the Foundations of Psychoanalysis\n\nThis community centers around the influential figures of Alfred Adler and Carl Jung, both of whom initially collaborated with Sigmund Freud but later developed their own distinct schools of thought—Individual Psychology and Analytical Psychology, respectively. Vienna, as the birthplace of psychoanalysis, serves as a historical and intellectual hub connecting these figures. The relationships between these entities highlight the evolution of psychoanalytic theory and the divergence from Freud's original ideas.\n\n## Adler's divergence from Freud and development of Individual Psychology\n\nAlfred Adler, a prominent psychoanalyst, initially followed Freud's theories but later diverged due to disagreements, particularly over Freud's emphasis on infantile sexuality. Adler developed Individual Psychology, which emphasizes the striving for superiority and