l dynamics in shaping personality and psychological well-being. Adler's emphasis on social factors has influenced various areas of psychology, including child development and therapeutic practices. [Data: Entities (670), Relationships (788)]\n\n## Analytical Psychology's focus on the collective unconscious\n\nAnalytical Psychology, developed by Jung, emphasizes the collective unconscious, archetypes, and the process of individuation. This school of thought diverges from Freudian theory by focusing on the symbolic dimensions of the human psyche and the shared, universal elements of human experience. Jung's concepts have had a profound impact on psychology, literature, and cultural studies, influencing the way we understand the human mind and its symbolic expressions. [Data: Entities (671), Relationships (784)]", "# Neo-Freudian Psychoanalysis and Key Contributors\n\nThe community centers around Neo-Freudian Psychoanalysis, a school of thought that diverged from Freud's original theories, with key contributors including Horney, Sullivan, Rank, and Jung. These psychoanalysts developed modified therapeutic techniques, emphasizing social, cultural, interpersonal, and birth trauma factors in psychological development. The relationships between Neo-Freudian Psychoanalysis and its contributors highlight the evolution and diversification of psychoanalytic theory.\n\n## Neo-Freudian Psychoanalysis as the central framework\n\nNeo-Freudian Psychoanalysis serves as the central framework of this community, representing a significant evolution from Freud's original theories. This school of thought incorporates modified and more active therapeutic techniques, emphasizing diverse factors such as social, cultural, interpersonal, and birth trauma influences. Its high degree of connectivity within the community underscores its importance in shaping modern psychoanalytic practices. [Data: Entities (673), Relationships (785, 794, 795, 796)]\n\n## Horney's emphasis on social and cultural 